--- AUTH & PERMISSIONS ---

[x] Basic login (Mastra SimpleAuth) — replaced by Supabase below
[x] Auth: Supabase + Google sign-in
    - Users sign in with Google via Supabase Auth
    - Supabase issues a JWT; Next.js proxy (proxy.ts) refreshes sessions
    - /auth/callback route exchanges OAuth code for a Supabase session
    - Next.js API route reads session.access_token and forwards it to Mastra
    - /chat/* routes are public on Mastra (optional auth); resourceId is
      injected server-side from session.user.id (authenticated) or a
      client-generated UUID per page load (guest — no persistence)
    - Mastra @mastra/auth-supabase verifies the JWT when present
    - Each signed-in user's Supabase UUID is their memory resourceId
    - Guest memory is ephemeral: fresh UUID per page load, nothing persists

[x] Remove mem0 — rely exclusively on Mastra built-in working memory
    - scope: "resource" stores working memory per resourceId across threads

[ ] Profile management: settings page for direct memory writes (no agent)
    - Build a form that directly calls:
        memory.updateWorkingMemory({ threadId: "any", resourceId: "<supabase-user-id>", workingMemory: string })
      `workingMemory` is the raw filled-in markdown template string. With scope:"resource"
      (already configured), threadId is ignored — only resourceId determines storage.
    - Read back with: memory.getWorkingMemory({ threadId: "any", resourceId: "<supabase-user-id>" })
    - Protect the API route so only the authenticated user can write their own profile

[ ] Cross-user read-only access (FGA)
    - Goal: user B can use the agent to find food FOR user A using A's dietary profile,
      but cannot modify A's profile.
    - Read path: user B's request includes user A's resourceId; Mastra reads A's working memory
      using memory.getReadOnlyWorkingMemoryInstruction() — a built-in Mastra helper that exposes
      the profile as context without allowing writes.
    - Write protection: wire Mastra FGA (MastraFGAPermissions.MEMORY_WRITE) so only the owner
      (user A) can write to resourceId A; all others get read-only thread access.
    - Requires FGA provider integration (e.g. Permit.io) on the Mastra server.
    - Mastra FGA hook: enforceThreadAccess() already checks MEMORY_WRITE permissions when
      a thread is accessed — just needs the FGA provider wired up.
